# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: game-input-handling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] DirectInput supports up to 128 buttons, 8 axes, and 4 point of view hats.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] While DirectInput forms a part of the DirectX library, it has not been significantly revised since DirectX 8 (2001–2002).
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] Microsoft recommends that new applications make use of the Windows message loop for keyboard and mouse input instead of DirectInput (as indicated in the Meltdown 2005 slideshow), and to use GameInput instead of legacy APIs such as DirectInput or XInput.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] DirectX included DirectInput from version 1.0 (1995).
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] It initially offered true support only for joysticks, as the mouse and keyboard modules simply provided wrappers to the standard Win32 API.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] DirectX version 3.0 (1996) added support for keyboards and mice; it also improved joystick support.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] DirectX 5.0 (1997) included greatly improved joystick support, including adding haptic feedback, increasing the number of buttons, changing the underlying device-driver model and incorporating a COM-based API.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] Mouse support also increased the number of buttons seen from four to eight.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] In DirectX 7.0 (1999- ), DirectInput added a long-promised feature of seeing individual mice much like individual joysticks, but the feature didn't work with the later released Windows XP, even though as of 2010 it works with Windows 98/Me and DirectX 9.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] DirectX 8.0 (2000), the last version with major changes, included action mapping and broader support for different types of devices.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] While Microsoft initially intended that DirectInput would handle all inputs, this didn't work out.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] As of 2011 Microsoft no longer recommends using DirectInput for keyboards or mice, and has started pushing the newer XInput for Xbox 360 controllers.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] In Windows Vista, Windows 7 and later Windows versions, the in-built action mapping UI has been removed.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] DirectInput is not available for Windows Store apps.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] XInput, a more recent but now legacy API for "next generation" controllers, was introduced in December 2005 alongside the launch of the Xbox 360.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] This specification provided support for Xbox 360 controllers in Windows XP SP1 and subsequent operating systems, and is described by Microsoft as being easier to program for and requiring less setup than DirectInput.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] XInput is compatible with DirectX version 9 and later.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] According to MSDN, "the combination of the left and right triggers in DirectInput is by design.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] Games have always assumed that DirectInput device axes are centered when there is no user interaction with the device.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] The above, however, ignores the fact that many DirectInput controllers, such as gamepads with dual analog sticks and racing-wheel controller sets, already map triggers and pedals independently.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] In addition, many DirectInput devices also have vibration effects.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] At least one 3rd-party driver, XBCD, gives the Xbox 360 controllers the vibration support, dead zones and (optionally) independent analog/digital triggers through DirectInput its XInput driver possesses.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] This suggests that Microsoft's Xbox 360 controller driver was given *intentionally* weaker DirectInput support, rather than due to any differences between DirectInput and XInput APIs.
[src:game-input-handling/directinput] On the other hand, Xbox 360 controllers using XInput support only very basic control of vibration motors in contrast with greater palette of effects supported via DirectInput.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] In computing, an **event** is a detectable occurrence or change in state that the system is designed to monitor, such as user input, hardware interrupt, system notification, or change in data or conditions.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] When associated with an event handler, an event triggers a response.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] The handler may run synchronously, where the execution thread is blocked until the event handler completes its processing, or asynchronously, where the event may be processed later.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Even when synchronous handling appears to block execution, the underlying mechanism in many systems is still asynchronous, managed by the event loop.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Events can be implemented through various mechanisms such as callbacks, message objects, signals, or interrupts, and events themselves are distinct from the implementation mechanisms used.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Event propagation models, such as bubbling, capturing, and pub/sub, define how events are distributed and handled within a system.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Other key aspects include event loops, event queueing and prioritization, event sourcing, and complex event processing patterns.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] These mechanisms contribute to the flexibility and scalability of event-driven systems.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] In distributed systems, event evolution poses challenges, such as managing inconsistent event schemas across services and ensuring compatibility during gradual system updates.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Event evolution strategies in event-driven architectures (EDA) can ensure that systems can handle changes to events without disruption.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] These strategies can include versioning events, such as semantic versioning or schema evolution, to maintain backward and forward compatibility.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Adapters can translate events between old and new formats, ensuring consistent processing across components.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] These techniques can enable systems to evolve while remaining compatible and reliable in complex, distributed environments.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] In computer science, an **event** (also called **event semaphore**) is a type of synchronization mechanism that is used to indicate to waiting processes when a particular condition has become true.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Different implementations of events may provide different subsets of these possible operations; for example, the implementation provided by Microsoft Windows provides the operations **wait** (WaitForObject and related functions), **set** (SetEvent), and **clear** (ResetEvent).
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] An option that may be specified during creation of the event object changes the behaviour of SetEvent so that only a single thread is released and the state is automatically returned to false after that thread is released.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Events short of **reset** function, that is, those which can be completed only once, are known as futures.
[src:game-input-handling/event-computing] Monitors are, on the other hand, more general since they combine completion signaling with mutex and do not let the producer and consumer to execute simultaneously in the monitor making it an event+critical section.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A **game controller**, **gaming controller**, or simply **controller**, is an input device or input/output device used with video games or entertainment systems to provide input to a video game.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Input devices that have been classified as game controllers include keyboards, mice, gamepads, and joysticks, as well as special purpose devices, such as steering wheels for driving games and light guns for shooting games.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Controllers designs have evolved to include directional pads, multiple buttons, analog sticks, joysticks, motion detection, touch screens and a plethora of other features.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Game controllers may be input devices that only provide input to the system, or input/output devices that receive data from the system and produce a response (e.g.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Controllers which are included with the purchase of a home console are referred to as standard controllers, while those that are available to purchase from the console manufacturer or third-party offerings are considered peripheral controllers.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] One of the first video game controllers was a simple dial and single button, used to control the game *Tennis for Two*.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Controllers have since evolved to include directional pads, multiple buttons, analog sticks, joysticks, motion detection, touch screens and a plethora of other features.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Game controllers have been designed and improved over the years to be as user friendly as possible.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The Microsoft Xbox controller, with its *shoulder triggers* that mimic actual triggers such as those found on guns, has become popular for shooting games.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] USB game controllers could also be connected to a computer with a USB port.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Input devices that have been classified as game controllers include keyboards, mouses, gamepads, and joysticks.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Special purpose devices, such as steering wheels for driving games and light guns for shooting games, are also game controllers.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Some controllers are designed to be best for one type of game, such as steering wheels for driving games, or dance pads for dancing games.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A gamepad, also known as a joypad, is held in both hands with thumbs and fingers used to provide input.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Gamepads can have a number of action buttons combined with one or more omnidirectional control sticks or buttons.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Action buttons are generally handled with the digits on the right hand, and the directional input handled with the left.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Gamepads are the primary means of input on most modern video game consoles.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Due to the ease of use and user-friendly nature of gamepads, they have spread from their origin on traditional consoles to personal computers, where a variety of games and emulators support their input as a replacement for keyboard and mouse input.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Most modern game controllers are a variation of a standard gamepad.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Common additions include shoulder buttons placed along the edges of the pad, centrally placed buttons labeled *start*, *select*, and *mode*, and an internal motor to provide haptic feedback.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] As modern game controllers advance, so too do their user ability qualities.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Typically, the controllers become smaller and more compact to more easily, and comfortably, fit within the user's hand.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Modern examples can be drawn from systems such as the first Xbox console, whose controller has changed in a variety of ways from the original Xbox 360 controller to the Xbox One controller introduced in 2013.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A paddle is a controller that features a round wheel and one or more fire buttons.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The wheel is typically used to control movement of the player or of an object along one axis of the video screen.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] As the user turns the wheel further from the default position, the speed of control in the game become more intensive.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Paddle controllers were the first analog controllers and they lost popularity when "paddle and ball" type games fell out of favor.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A variation, the Atari driving controller, appeared on the Atari 2600.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Designed specifically for the game *Indy 500*, it functioned almost identically in operation and design to the regular paddle controller.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The exceptions were that its wheel could be continuously rotated in either direction, and that it was missing the extra paddle included on the previous model.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Unlike a spinner, friction prevented the wheel from gaining momentum.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A joystick is a peripheral that consists of a handheld stick that can be tilted around either of two axes and (sometimes) twisted around a third.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The joystick is often used for flight simulators.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] HOTAS (hands on throttle and stick) controllers, composed of a joystick and throttle quadrant (see below) are a popular combination for flight simulation among its most fanatic devotees.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Most joysticks are designed to be operated with the user's primary hand (e.g. with the right hand of a right-handed person), with the base either held in the opposite hand or mounted on a desk.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Arcade controllers are typically joysticks featuring a shaft that has a ball or drop-shaped handle, and one or more buttons for in game actions.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Generally the layout has the joystick on the left, and the buttons on the right, although there are instances when this is reversed.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A trackball is a smooth sphere that is manipulated with the palm of one's hand.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The user can roll the ball in any direction to control the cursor.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] It has the advantage that it can be faster than a mouse depending on the speed of rotation of the physical ball.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Another advantage is that it requires less space than a mouse, which the trackball was a precursor of.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Notable uses of a Trackball as a gaming controller would be games such as *Centipede*, *Marble Madness*, *Golden Tee Golf* and *SegaSonic the Hedgehog*.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A throttle quadrant is a set of one or more throttle levers that are most often used to simulate throttles or other similar controls in a real vehicle, particularly an aircraft.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Throttle quadrants are most popular in conjunction with joysticks or yokes used in flight simulation.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A racing wheel, essentially a larger version of a paddle, is used in most racing arcade games as well as more recent racing simulators such as *Live for Speed*, *Grand Prix Legends*, *GTR2*, and *Richard Burns Rally*.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] While most arcade racing games have been using steering wheels since *Gran Trak 10* in 1974, steering wheels for home systems appeared on fifth-generation consoles such as the PlayStation and Nintendo 64.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Many are force feedback (see Force Feedback Wheel), designed to give the same feedback as would be experienced when driving a real car, but the realism of this depends on the game.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] They usually come with pedals to control the gas and brake.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Shifting is taken care of in various ways including paddle shifting systems, simple stick shifters which are moved forward or back to change gears or more complex shifters which mimic those of real vehicles, which may also use a clutch.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Some wheels turn only 200 to 270 degrees lock-to-lock but higher-tier models can turn 900 degrees, or 2.5 turns, lock-to-lock, or more.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The Namco Jogcon paddle was available for the PlayStation game *R4: Ridge Racer Type 4*.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Unlike "real" video game steering wheels, the Jogcon was designed to fit in the player's hand.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Its much smaller wheel (diameter roughly similar to a soda can's) resembles the jog-and-shuttle control wheel used on some VCRs.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The Wii game *Mario Kart Wii* is bundled with the Wii Wheel: a steering wheel-shaped shell that the Wii Remote is placed inside thus using the Wii Remote's motion sensing capabilities to control the kart during the game.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Hori also has a steering wheel that is made for the Nintendo 3DS game *Mario Kart 7*.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] When the steering wheel is placed on the back of the console, then it will have the same ability as in *Mario Kart Wii* by using the gyroscope in first-person mode.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A yoke is very similar to a steering wheel except that it resembles the control yoke found on many aircraft and has two axes of movement: not only rotational movement about the shaft of the yoke, but also a forward-and-backward axis equivalent to that of pitch control on the yoke of an aircraft.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Some yokes have additional controls attached directly to the yoke for simulation of aircraft functions such as radio push-to-talk buttons.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Some flight simulator sets that include yokes also come with various other aircraft controls such as throttle quadrants and pedals.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] These sets, including the yoke, are intended to be used in a flight simulator.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Pedals may be used for driving simulations or flight simulations and often ships with a steering-wheel-type input device.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] In the former case, an asymmetric set of pedals can simulate accelerator, brake, and clutch pedals in a real automobile.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] In the latter case, a symmetric set of pedals simulates rudder controls and toe brakes in an aircraft.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] As mentioned, most steering wheel controllers come with a set of pedals.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] There are also variations of the pedal controller such as the proposed rotating pedal device for a cycling game, which relies on an ergometer to generate user inputs such as pedal rpm and pedal resistance.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A variation of this concept surfaced in 2016 when a startup called VirZoom debuted a set of sensors that can be installed in the pedal and handlebars, turning a physical bike into one controller for games on the HTC Vive and Oculus Rift virtual reality (VR) platforms.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The same concept is behind a product called Cyber ExerCycle, which is a set of sensors attached to the pedal and connected to the PC via USB for bicycle simulation games such as NetAthlon and Fuel.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A mouse and computer keyboard are typical input devices for a personal computer and are currently the main game controllers for computer games.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The mouse is often used with a mousepad to achieve greater speed, comfort, accuracy and smoother movement for the gamer.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Some video game consoles also have the ability to function with a keyboard and a mouse.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The computer keyboard is modelled after the typewriter keyboard and was designed for the input of written text.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A mouse is a handheld pointing device used in addition to the keyboard.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] For games, the keyboard typically controls movement of the character while the mouse is used to control the game camera or used for aiming.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] While originally designed for general computer input, there are several keyboard and mouse peripherals available which are designed specifically for gaming, often with gaming-specific functions built-in.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Examples include peripherals by Razer, the "Zboard" range of keyboards and Logitech's 'G' series.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The numeric keypad found on the keyboard is also used as a game controller and can be found on a number of separate devices, most notably early consoles, usually attached to a joystick or a paddle.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The keypad is a small grid of keys with at least the digits 0–9.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A gaming keypad is a specialized controller used for FPSs, RTSs and some arcade type games.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] These controllers can be programmed to allow the emulation of keys, and macros in some cases.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] These generally resemble a small part of a keyboard but may also feature other inputs such as analog sticks.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Johnson, head of Split Fish Gameware, introduced a first of its kind design, Dual Mouse/Motion Nunchuck, two part Combo controller, for PlayStation 2 called "FragFx" to improve accuracy of FPS gaming on consoles and emulate the feel of a mouse and keyboard input similar to PC gaming.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] They were developed because some of these games require a keyboard to play, and some players find this to be awkward for such a task.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The mouse and keyboard input is also known by the abbreviation "MnK".
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A touchscreen is an input device that allows the user to interact with the computer by touching the display screen.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The first attempt at a handheld game console with touchscreen controls was Sega's intended successor to the Game Gear, though the device was ultimately shelved and never released due to the high cost of touchscreen technology in the early 1990s.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The first released console to use a touchscreen was the Tiger game.com in 1997.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Nintendo popularized it for use in video games with the Nintendo DS and Nintendo 3DS; other systems including the Tapwave Zodiac as well as Smartphones and the vast majority of PDAs have also included this feature.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The primary controller for Nintendo's Wii U console, the Wii U GamePad, features an embedded touchscreen.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Modern touch screens use a thin, durable, transparent plastic sheet overlaid onto a glass screen.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The location of a touch is calculated from the capacitance for the X and Y axes, which varies based upon where the sheet is touched.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] One console that is touchscreen developed by Sony is the PlayStation Vita which has a 5-inch OLED touchscreen.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The Nintendo Switch features a 6.2 inch touchscreen, whereas its successor, the Nintendo Switch 2 features a 7.9 inch touchscreen.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Motion controllers include the Sega Activator, released in 1993 for the Mega Drive (Genesis).
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Based on the Light Harp invented by Assaf Gurner, it could read the player's physical movements and was the first controller to allow full-body motion sensing.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] However, it was a commercial failure due to its "unwieldiness and inaccuracy".
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Nintendo's Wii system released in 2006 utilizes the Wii Remote controller, which uses accelerometers to detect its approximate orientation and acceleration and an image sensor, so it can be used as a pointing device.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The Sixaxis, DualShock 3, and PlayStation Move controllers for Sony's PlayStation 3 system have similar motion sensing capabilities.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Johnson, head of Split Fish Gameware, introduced a first of its kind, Dual Mouse/Motion Nunchuck Combo controller for PlayStation 2 called "FragFx" to improve accuracy of FPS gaming on consoles.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] In 2010, Microsoft released the Kinect for the Xbox 360.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] This motion sensing controller uses cameras to track a player's movement.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Microsoft released a revised version of the Kinect with the launch of the Xbox One.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] This controller was bundled with the console on launch, and was removed from the default bundle in June 2014.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Sony's EyeToy similarly uses cameras to detect the player's motions and translate them into inputs for the game.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Controllers with gyroscopes may be used to create a pointer without a camera; for example the Joy-Con and Nintendo Switch Pro Controller are used for this in games such as ports of World of Goo and Super Mario Galaxy from the Wii.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] An adaptive controller is collections of various input methods that can be combined in multiple ways to create a controller that works for the user.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The adaptive controller was designed for people with physical disabilities that would prevent them from using a gamepad or mouse and keyboard.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] An example would be PlayStation's access controller that was released in December 2023 which allows for a large joystick, eight buttons on a circular pad, and four ports to plug in additional buttons or accessories.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Xbox and Logitech have collaborated to make an adaptive controller with two large touch pads, a D-pad, three buttons, and 16 ports to plug in additional accessories.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] These accessories can include joysticks, pedals, triggers and buttons.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A light gun is a peripheral used to "shoot" targets on a screen.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] They usually roughly resemble firearms or ray guns.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Their use is normally limited to rail shooters, or shooting gallery games like Duck Hunt and those which came with the *Shooting Gallery* light gun.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] A rare example of a non-rail first person shooter game is Taito's 1992 video game *Gun Buster*, a first-person shooter that used a joystick to move and a light gun to aim.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Though light guns have been used in earlier arcade games such as Sega's *Periscope* in 1966 and *Missile* in 1969, the first home console light gun was released for the Magnavox Odyssey in 1972; later on, Nintendo would include one standard on their Famicom and NES, called the NES Zapper.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Nintendo has also released a "shell" in the style of a light gun for the more recent Wii Remote called the Wii Zapper which comes bundled with the game *Link's Crossbow Training*.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Other rhythm games are based around the art of Djing or turntablism (*DJ Hero*), or playing a synthesizer (*IIDX*) using a turntable shaped peripheral with buttons.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Wireless versions of many popular controller types (joypads, mice, keyboards) exist, and wireless motion controls are an emerging class for virtual reality.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Although gamepads are generally developed for use with consoles, they are also often used for PC gaming and mobile gaming.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Modern controllers, such as Sony's Sixaxis/DualShock 3/4/DualSense, Nintendo's Switch Pro Controller/Switch 2 Pro Controller and Valve's Steam Controller, support USB and Bluetooth, allowing them to be directly connected to most PCs.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Older gamepads can be connected through the use of official or third-party adapters.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Controllers typically require the installation of device drivers to be used on contemporary personal computers.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The device may be directly supported, or it may require the use of a specialized program which maps controller inputs to mouse and keyboard inputs.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Examples of this kind of software include JoyToKey, Xpadder, and antimicro, which is free, open-source, and cross-platform.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Some controllers are specially designed for usage outside of consoles.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] In this case, support for mapping to different devices is built into the controller itself, such as with the Nostromo SpeedPad n52, which can act as either a keyboard, mouse, or joystick; or with the Samsung Android GamePad and Backbone One/Pro, designed for use with Android mobile phones.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] The usage of gamepads over the mouse and keyboard has been referred to as a debate, with players of MMORPGs, RTS games, and first-person shooters tending to prefer the mouse and keyboard due to the wider variety of inputs and the high precision of the mouse when compared to an analog stick.
[src:game-input-handling/game-controller] Likewise, players of racing games, fighting games, and action RPGs tend to prefer controllers for their analog inputs and ergonomic button layouts.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] A **gamepad** is a type of video game controller held in two hands, where the fingers (especially thumbs) are used to provide input.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Typically the primary input device for video game consoles, gamepads feature a set of buttons and often one or more omnidirectional control sticks.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] First appearing in the early 1960s with custom devices for games like *Spacewar!*, the gamepad rose to mass-market prominence during the third generation of video game consoles with the introduction of the NES controller and its iconic D-pad.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Since then, the design has undergone continued refinements, including the addition of shoulder buttons, analog triggers, and haptic feedback.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] While primarily designed for consoles, modern gamepads are also widely used on personal computers and have occasionally been adapted for non-gaming purposes, such as controlling military equipment or submersibles.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Analog triggers, like that of the GameCube controller, are pressure-sensitive and games can read in the amount of pressure applied to one to control the intensity of a certain action, such as how forceful water is to be sprayed in *Super Mario Sunshine*.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] There are programmable joysticks that can emulate keyboard input.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Generally they have been made to circumvent the lack of joystick support in some computer games, e.g. the Belkin Nostromo SpeedPad n52.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] There are several programs that emulate keyboard and mouse input with a gamepad such as the free and open-source cross-platform software antimicro, Enjoy2, or proprietary commercial solutions such as JoyToKey, Xpadder, and Pinnacle Game Profiler.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] One common issue with modern game controllers is stick drift, where the analog stick registers movement even when not being touched.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] This problem can affect gameplay accuracy and responsiveness.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Stick drift is a common technical issue in modern analog sticks where movement is registered without user input.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] This phenomenon has led to the development of diagnostic software and web-based tools that visualize input accuracy.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Such tools are used to identify the need for hardware maintenance or recalibration.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Some platforms, like Steam, also include built-in calibration settings to mitigate minor drift issues.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The 1962 video game *Spacewar!* initially used toggle switches built into the computer readout display to control the game.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] These switches were awkward and uncomfortable to use, so Alan Kotok and Bob Saunders built and wired in a detached control device for the game.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] This device has been called the earliest gamepad.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] It would take many years for the gamepad to rise to prominence, as during the 1970s and the early 1980s joysticks and paddles were the dominant video game controllers, though several Atari joystick port-compatible pushbutton controllers were also available.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The third generation of video games saw many major changes, and the eminence of gamepads in the video game market.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Nintendo developed a gamepad device for directional inputs, a D-pad with a "cross" design for their *Donkey Kong* handheld game.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] This design would be incorporated into their "Game & Watch" series and console controllers such as the standard NES controller.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Though developed because they were more compact than joysticks, and thus more appropriate for handheld games, D-pads were soon found by developers to be more comfortable to use than joysticks.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The D-pad soon became a ubiquitous element on console gamepads, though to avoid infringing on Nintendo's patent, most controller manufacturers use a cross in a circle shape for the D-pad instead of a simple cross.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The original Sega Genesis/Mega Drive control pad has three face buttons, but a six-button pad was later released.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The SNES controller also featured six action buttons, with four face buttons arranged in a diamond formation, and two shoulder buttons positioned to be used with the index fingers, a design which has been imitated by most controllers since.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The inclusion of six action buttons was influenced by the popularity of the *Street Fighter* arcade series, which utilized six buttons.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] For most of the 1980s and early 1990s, analog joysticks were the predominant form of gaming controller for PCs, while console gaming controllers were mostly digital.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] This changed in 1996 when all three major consoles introduced an optional analog control.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The Sony Dual Analog Controller had twin convex analog thumbsticks, the Sega Saturn 3D Control Pad had a single analog thumbstick, and the Nintendo 64 controller combined digital and analog controllers in a single body, starting a trend to have both an analog stick and a d-pad.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Despite these changes, gamepads essentially continued to follow the template set by the NES controller (a horizontally-oriented controller with two or more action buttons positioned for use with the right thumb, and a directional pad positioned for use with the left thumb).
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Though three-dimensional games rose to prominence in the mid-1990s, controllers continued to mostly operate on two-dimensional principles.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Players would have to hold down a button to change the axes along which the controls operate rather than being able to control movement along all three axes at once.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] One of the first gaming consoles, the Fairchild Channel F, did have a controller which provided six degrees of freedom, but the processing limitations of the console itself prevented there from being any software to take advantage of this ability.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] In 1994, Logitech introduced the CyberMan, the first practical six-degrees-of-freedom controller; however, it sold poorly due to its high price, poor build quality, and limited software support.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Industry insiders blame the CyberMan's high profile and costly failure for the gaming industry's lack of interest in developing 3D control over the next several years.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The Wii Remote is shaped like a television remote control and contains tilt sensors and three-dimensional pointing which the system uses to understand all directions of movement and rotation (back and forth around the pitch, roll, and yaw axes).
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The controller is also multifunctional and has an expansion port which can be used for a variety of peripherals.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] An analog stick peripheral, called "Nunchuk," also contains an accelerometer but unlike the Wii Remote, it lacks any pointer functionality.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Gamepads may be gripped differently for better ergonomics or a gaming advantage.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The standard grip involves operating the trigger buttons with the index fingers, with the thumbs operating both the analog sticks and digital buttons.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] This grip is common among gamers, but it leaves the thumbs unable to operate the digital buttons while operating the analog sticks, and vice versa, leading to a time consuming alternation.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The claw grip attempts to alleviate the standard grip's problem of alternation by operating the trigger buttons with the middle fingers, the directional buttons with the index fingers and the analog sticks with the thumbs.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] This grip may be used exclusively, or with only one hand, with the other hand using the standard grip.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The claw grip is named as such because the player's index fingers take the shape of a claw or hook when used.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The claw grip may cause pain or injury due to strain on the index finger.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Although the grip is commonly used in certain games, player Nickmercs warned his audience that the claw grip may cause complications in 2019.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Gamepads are also available for personal computers.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Examples of PC gamepads include the Asus Eee Stick, the Gravis PC, the Microsoft SideWinder and Saitek Cyborg range, and the Steam Controller.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] Gamepads or devices closely modelled on them are sometimes used for controlling real machinery and vehicles, as they are familiar to users and (in the case of actual gamepads) provide an off-the-shelf solution.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The US Army and US Navy use Xbox controllers for operating devices, and the British Army uses a device modelled on gamepads to operate systems on the Challenger 2 main battle tank.
[src:game-input-handling/gamepad] The *Titan* submersible used a gamepad for control.
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] A **human interface device** (**HID**) is a type of computer device usually used by humans that takes input from or provides output to humans.
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] The term "HID" most commonly refers to the USB HID specification.
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] The term was coined by Mike Van Flandern of Microsoft when he proposed that the USB committee create a Human Input Device class working group.
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] The working group was renamed as the Human Interface Device class at the suggestion of Tom Schmidt of DEC because the proposed standard supported bidirectional communication.
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] A working committee with representatives from several prominent companies developed the HID standard.
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] The list of participants appears in the "Device Class Definition for Human Interface Devices (HID)" document.
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] SIM was also self-describing and extensible, however it was more focused on SIMulation devices used for VR and motion capture.
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] After comparing notes at a Consumer Game Developer Conference, Steve and Mike agreed to collaborate on a new standard for the emerging Universal Serial Bus (USB).
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] Since HID's original definition over USB, HID is now also used in other computer communication buses.
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] This enables HID devices that traditionally were only found on USB to also be used on alternative buses.
[src:game-input-handling/human-interface-device] This is done since existing support for USB HID devices can typically be adapted much faster than having to invent an entirely new protocol to support mouse, touchpad, keyboards, and the like.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] In computing, an **input device** is a piece of equipment used to enter data and control signals to an information processing system, such as a computer or information appliance.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Examples of input devices include keyboards, computer mice, scanners, cameras, joysticks, and microphones.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] A **keyboard** is a human interface device which is represented as a matrix of buttons.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Each button, or key, can be used to either input an alphanumeric character to a computer, or to call upon a particular function of the computer.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] It acts as the main text entry interface for most users..
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Keyboards are available in many form factors, depending on the use case.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Standard keyboards can be categorized by its size and number of keys, and the type of switch it employs.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Other keyboards cater to specific use cases, such as a numeric keypad or a keyer.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Desktop keyboards are typically large, often have full key travel distance, and features such as multimedia keys and a numeric keypad.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Keyboards on laptops and tablets typically compromise on comfort to achieve a thin figure.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] There are various switch technologies used in modern keyboards, such as mechanical switches (which use springs), scissor switches (usually found on a laptop keyboard), or a membrane.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Other keyboards do not have physical keys, such as a virtual keyboard, or a projection keyboard.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] A keyboard used by pressing several keys together.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] While some keyboards include one (commonly found on the right side), numeric keypads can be found as independent devices.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] A **pointing device** allows a user to input spatial data to a computer.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] It is commonly used as a simple and intuitive way to select items on a computer screen on a graphical user interface (GUI), either by moving a mouse pointer, or, in the case of a touch screen, by physically touching the item on screen.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Common pointing devices include mice, touchpads, and touch screens.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Whereas mice operate by detecting their displacement on a surface, analog devices, such as 3D mice, joysticks, or pointing sticks, function by reporting their angle of deflection.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Direct input is almost necessarily absolute, but indirect input may be either absolute or relative.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Embedded LCD tablets, which are also referred to as graphics tablet monitors, are the extension of digitizing graphics tablets.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] They enable users to see the real-time positions via the screen while being used.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] A hand-held pointing device that is moved across a surface.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] A flat surface operated by moving a finger across its surface.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] , used by physically touching it with one's finger or a stylus.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Similar to a mouse, a trackball has a ball held by a socket.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Instead of moving the mouse, the user rolls the ball with their finger.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] is used, often to draw images or capture signatures.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] A **sensor** is an input device which produces data based on physical properties.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Sensors are commonly found in mobile devices to detect their physical orientation and acceleration, but may also be found in desktop computers in the form of a thermometer used to monitor system temperature.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Detects whether an object is in proximity.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Some sensors can be built with MEMS, which allows them to be microscopic in size.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Some devices allow many continuous degrees of freedom as input.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] These can be used as pointing devices, but are generally used in ways that don't involve pointing to a location in space, such as the control of a camera angle while in 3D applications.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] These kinds of devices are typically used in virtual reality systems (CAVEs), where input that registers six degrees of freedom is required.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Input devices, such as buttons and joysticks, can be combined on a single physical device that could be thought of as a composite device.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Many gaming devices have controllers like this.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Technically mice are composite devices, as they both track movement and provide buttons for clicking, but composite devices are generally considered to have more than two different forms of input.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Consists of a stick pivoting on a stationary base.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Video input devices are used to digitize images or video from the outside world into the computer.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] The information can be stored in a multitude of formats depending on the user's requirement.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Many video input devices use a camera sensor.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Voice input devices are used to capture sound.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] In some cases, an audio output device can be used as an input device, in order to capture produced sound.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Audio input devices allow a user to send audio info to a computer for processing, recording, or carrying out commands.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Devices such as microphones allow users to speak to the computer in order to record a voice message or navigate software.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Aside from recording, audio input devices are also used with speech recognition software.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] Punched cards and punched tapes were used often in the 20th century.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] A punched hole represented a one; its absence represented a zero.
[src:game-input-handling/input-device] A mechanical or optical reader was used to input a punched card or tape.
